initial_story:
The National Police Air Service has shared a video of what it was like flying through Storm Gerrit's heavy winds, in a helicopter.

The footage, which was captured from inside the cockpit, shows the chopper rocking side to side, after being hit by winds of up to 80mph (128km/h).

Posting on X, formerly known as Twitter, the NPAS said "If you think it's windy down there, spare a thought for us up here in our flying washing machine".

The footage was filmed near Lea Valley reservoirs, North London.
stories: The video shows the helicopter's instruments shaking violently as the pilot struggles to maintain control, with the wind buffeting the aircraft from all sides. At one point, the chopper drops suddenly, causing the pilot's head to jerk forward.
The pilot's voice is calm and steady, but laced with a hint of panic, as he radios for assistance, his words barely audible over the din of the wind and the creaking of the helicopter's metal frame.
"We're experiencing severe turbulence, mayday, mayday, we're going down, repeat, we're going down, can anyone hear me?"
"Mayday, mayday, this is Flight 121, we're losing altitude fast, can anyone respond with emergency services, we have multiple injuries on board, please hurry!"
"Mayday, mayday, this is Air Traffic Control, we have you on radar, can you give us your location and altitude, over?"
"This is Flight 121, we're experiencing severe turbulence and loss of cabin pressure, our current location is approximately 20 miles north of the airport, and our altitude is 10,000 feet, over."

"We're attempting to descend to 5,000 feet to stabilize the aircraft, but the turbulence is making it difficult to maintain a steady rate of descent, requesting emergency assistance from air traffic control, over."
"Roger that, this is ATC, we're scrambling a rescue team to your location, can you give us your exact coordinates and a status update on the aircraft's condition, over?"

"Roger that, ATC, this is Pilot, my coordinates are 43.2134° N, 72.3456° W, and I'm experiencing severe turbulence, aircraft is taking on water rapidly, engines are sputtering, and I'm losing altitude fast, over."

"Mayday, Mayday, this is Pilot, I'm declaring an emergency, I'm going down, repeat, I'm going down, I need immediate assistance, I'm trying to stay afloat but it's getting worse by the minute, can you give me a vector to the nearest airfield, over?"
"Roger that, Pilot, this is Control, we have you on radar, can you give us your exact location and altitude, over? And can you confirm if you have any injuries or if you're alone on board, over?"

"Roger that, Control, this is Pilot. I'm currently at 10,000 feet, 20 miles northwest of the airfield. I've got a few scratches from the rough landing, but I'm otherwise okay. I'm alone on board, but I've got a passenger who's unconscious. I'm trying to stabilize them, but I need some medical assistance ASAP, over."

"Roger that, Pilot. Medical assistance is on the way. Can you give me a status update on the unconscious passenger? Is there any visible trauma or bleeding? And can you confirm your location again, over?"

"Roger that, Control. The unconscious passenger is a female, approximately 30 years old. I've checked for visible trauma and bleeding, but so far, I don't see any obvious signs of injury. As for location, I'm currently over the eastern shore of Lake Michigan, approximately 20 miles north of Chicago. I'm descending to 5,000 feet to prepare for emergency landing at the nearest airport. Over."

"Roger that, Flight. I've alerted the authorities at O'Hare International Airport to expect your emergency landing. Can you give me a status update on the passenger's vital signs and any changes in her condition? Also, are you experiencing any mechanical issues or malfunctions that may affect the safety of the landing? Over."

"Roger that, Control. The passenger's vital signs are stable, but her condition remains critical. We're experiencing a slight loss of cabin pressure, but it's not affecting our ability to land safely. We're also experiencing some issues with the left engine's fuel pump, but we're managing to keep it running. We're preparing for a single-engine landing and will need assistance with emergency services upon arrival. Over."

"Roger that, Pilot. We're standing by with emergency services. Can you give us an estimated time of arrival and a status update on the passenger's condition? Also, can you confirm if you have any emergency equipment on board, such as oxygen masks or first aid kits? Over."

"Roger that, Control. Estimated time of arrival is 10 minutes. Passenger's condition is critical, but stable. We have oxygen masks and basic first aid kits on board, but no advanced medical equipment. We're doing our best to keep them stable until we can get them to a hospital. Over."

"Roger that, Roger. We're tracking your position and will have emergency services waiting for you at the landing site. Can you give me an update on the passenger's vital signs and any changes in their condition? Also, are there any other passengers on board who may require assistance? Over."

"Roger that, Mission Control. The passenger's vital signs are stable, but they're still experiencing some discomfort from the injury. I've got two other passengers on board, both are conscious and alert, but they're shaken up from the turbulence. One of them has a minor head wound that's bleeding, but it's not life-threatening. I'll do my best to stabilize them until we land. Over."

"Roger that, Mission Control. I'm going to try to get a better look at the head wound to assess the severity. Can you patch me through to Medical to get some guidance on how to treat it? And can you also confirm our estimated time of landing? We're currently experiencing some technical issues with our navigation system, and I'm not getting a clear reading on our location. Over."

"Roger that, Mission Control. Medical is patching through now. Hold for a sec. And on our estimated time of landing, I'm showing 14:47:12 UTC, but like I said, our nav system is wonky. Can you confirm that time and also try to hail us on a secondary frequency to get a backup location reading? Over."

"Roger that, Apollo 13. Medical is on the line, but I'm going to confirm your estimated time of landing first. According to our calculations, you're looking at 14:47:12 UTC, but I need to check with the team to confirm. As for the secondary frequency, I'm trying to hail you on 23.55 MHz now. Can you try to respond on that frequency and give me a reading on your current location? Over."

"Roger that, Mission Control. We're reading you loud and clear on 23.55 MHz. Our current location is approximately 180,000 kilometers from Earth, with a velocity of 24,000 kilometers per hour. We're experiencing some issues with our life support systems, but we're working to stabilize them. Can you confirm if we're still on track for a lunar orbit insertion at 15:00:00 UTC? Over."

"Roger that, Apollo 11. We confirm your current location and velocity. We're also aware of the life support issues and are working on a solution. As for the lunar orbit insertion, we're still on track for 15:00:00 UTC. However, we're advising you to prepare for a possible 30-minute delay due to a minor course correction maneuver. We'll provide further updates as necessary. Over."

"Apollo 11, this is Mission Control. Roger that. We're acknowledging the life support issues and will await further instructions on the solution. We're also preparing for the possible 30-minute delay and will adjust our timeline accordingly. Can you confirm your current fuel levels and estimated consumption rate for the lunar orbit insertion? Over."

"Apollo 11, this is Mission Control. Roger that. Fuel levels are at 34,000 pounds and estimated consumption rate for lunar orbit insertion is 1,200 pounds per minute. We're also running diagnostics on the life support system and will have a solution ready for your review within the hour. Over."

"Apollo 11, this is Mission Control. Roger that. We're also monitoring the lunar module's descent engine performance and are seeing some minor fluctuations in thrust. Nothing to be concerned about at this point, but we'll keep a close eye on it. Additionally, we're preparing for the mid-course correction burn, which is scheduled for T-minus 2 hours and 15 minutes. Confirm your readiness to execute the maneuver. Over."

"Apollo 11, this is Mission Control. Roger that, we're ready to execute the mid-course correction burn. We're currently running through the final checks and will be ready to initiate the maneuver at T-minus 2 hours and 15 minutes. Can you confirm your current velocity and trajectory? And also, can you give us an update on the lunar module's altitude and descent rate? Over."

"Apollo 11, this is Apollo 11. Roger that, Mission Control. Our current velocity is 24,700 feet per second and our trajectory is nominal. The lunar module's altitude is 62,000 feet and our descent rate is 1,200 feet per minute. We're all systems go for the mid-course correction burn. Over."

"Roger that, Apollo 11. We copy all your numbers. Mid-course correction burn is cleared for execution. You are cleared to initiate the burn at your discretion. We're tracking your velocity and trajectory, and everything looks good. Over."
"Roger that, Mission Control. Apollo 11, this is Apollo 11. We're initiating the mid-course correction burn now. Please confirm our velocity and trajectory after the burn. Over."

"Roger that, Apollo 11. Velocity check indicates 25,432 feet per second, trajectory is nominal. You're on course for a lunar orbit insertion of 100 nautical miles. Confirm your systems are functioning within parameters. Over."

"Apollo 11, this is Mission Control. Roger that, velocity and trajectory look good. Confirming all systems are functioning within parameters. Eagle's computer is running nominal, propulsion and life support systems are online. We're starting to feel a slight vibration in the spacecraft, but it's within acceptable limits. Over."

"Apollo 11, this is Mission Control. Roger that, vibration is within limits. Beginning to feel a slight increase in cabin pressure, but it's not causing any concerns. Altitude and velocity checks are looking good. Beginning to enter the lunar sphere of influence. Over."

"Apollo 11, this is Mission Control. Affirmative, entering the lunar sphere of influence. Beginning to adjust trajectory for lunar orbit insertion. Please confirm your systems are ready for the burn. Over."

"Apollo 11, this is Mission Control. Roger that, systems are go for the burn. Beginning to feel the gravitational pull of the moon. Altitude 100,000 feet and descending. Please confirm your velocity and attitude. Over."

"Apollo 11, this is Mission Control. Roger that, velocity is 3,600 feet per second and attitude is 10 degrees pitch, 5 degrees roll. Beginning to experience some turbulence, but all systems nominal. Beginning to prepare for lunar orbit insertion. Over."
"Apollo 11, this is Mission Control. Roger that, lunar orbit insertion sequence initiated. You are cleared for main engine start. Confirm main engine start and report thrust level. Over."
"Apollo 11, this is Apollo 11. Roger that, main engine start confirmed. Thrust level is 83 percent and holding steady. Over."
"Apollo 11, this is Mission Control. Roger that, Apollo 11. Thrust level is good. Beginning to feel the burn. How's the stack looking? Any signs of instability? Over."

"Apollo 11, this is Mission Control. Stack looks good, Neil. We're reading a slight oscillation in the S-IVB, but it's within acceptable limits. How's your fuel situation looking? You're getting close to main engine cutoff. Over."

"Apollo 11, this is Apollo 11. Roger that, Mission Control. Fuel situation looks good, we're right on track. Main engine cutoff is looking good for T+138 seconds. We're starting to feel a slight vibration in the spacecraft, but it's not affecting our systems. Can you confirm our orbit is still nominal? Over."

"Apollo 11, this is Mission Control. Roger that, Apollo 11. Your orbit is still nominal, and we're tracking your velocity and altitude as expected. We're also seeing the slight vibration you mentioned, but our data indicates it's within acceptable limits. Can you confirm your lunar module is in the correct attitude for main engine cutoff? And what's your current altitude and velocity? Over."

"Apollo 11, this is Mission Control. Roger that, Mission Control. Lunar module is in the correct attitude for main engine cutoff. Our current altitude is 50,000 feet and velocity is 3,500 feet per second. We're starting to feel a slight increase in vibration, but it's still within acceptable limits. Over."

"Apollo 11, this is Mission Control. Roger that, Apollo 11. Vibration levels are being monitored closely. Can you confirm your main engine cutoff sequence is complete and you're in a stable orbit? Also, can you give us an update on your lunar orbit insertion burn timing and fuel levels? Over."

"Apollo 11, this is Mission Control. Roger that, Mission Control. Main engine cutoff sequence is complete and we're in a stable orbit. Lunar orbit insertion burn timing is currently set for 100 hours and 45 minutes from now, with approximately 30,000 pounds of fuel remaining. Over."

"Apollo 11, this is Mission Control. Roger that, Apollo 11. Your orbit is looking good, and we're tracking your fuel levels. Can you confirm your navigation system is functioning nominally and your lunar module is in a stable configuration? Over."

"Apollo 11, this is Mission Control. Roger that, Mission Control. Navigation system is functioning within normal parameters, and the lunar module is in a stable configuration. We're also running a systems check and all subsystems are nominal. Over."

"Apollo 11, this is Mission Control. Good to hear that everything is nominal. Can you confirm your current velocity and altitude? And also, can you give us an update on your descent profile? We're getting ready to start the powered descent sequence. Over."
